      "everse\n    unfold List.init\n    cases as with\n    | nil =>\n      simp\n      cases bs with\n      | nil =>\n        simp [SymList.init, SymList.reverse, SymList.tailSL, SymList.nil]\n      | cons n ns =>\n        simp [SymList.init, SymList.reverse, SymList.tailSL, SymList.nil]\n        sorry\n```\n\nWe need to complete the proof. The goal is:\n`List.init (sl.fromSL) = sl.init.fromSL`\n\nAfter unfolding:\n- `List.init` is defined as `match l with | [] => [] | [_] => [] | x :: xs => x :: List.init xs`\n- `SymList.init` is `q.reverse.tailSL.reverse`\n- `SymList.reverse` is `⟨as, bs, ok⟩ => ⟨bs, as, by exact And.intro ok.2 ok.1⟩`\n- `SymList.tailSL` is `⟨as, bs, ok⟩ => ⟨as, List.tail bs, ok'⟩` (where `ok'` is the predicate applied to `List.tail bs`)\n- `SymList.nil` is `⟨[], [], true⟩` (or similar, depending on the exact definition)\n\nLet's continue with the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter3\nimport Fad.Chapter1\n\nnamespace Assignment03\n\ndef compress (s : String) : List (Nat × Nat) :=\n  help (s.toList.map (·.toNat - '0'.toNat)) []\n where\n  help : List Nat → List (Nat × Nat) → List (Nat × Nat)\n  | []     , acc      => acc.reverse\n  | x :: xs, []       => help xs [(x, 1)]\n  | x :: xs, p :: acc =>\n    if x = p.1\n    then help xs ((p.1, p.2 + 1) :: acc)\n    else help xs ((x, 1) :: p :: acc)\n\n-- #eval compress \"1333332222211\" -- returns [(1, 1), (3, 5), (2, 5), (1, 2)]\n\ndef uncompress : List (Nat × Nat) → String :=\n  let h (xs : List Nat) := xs.foldr (λ a r => s!\"{a}{r}\") \"\"\n  List.foldr (λ p r => h (List.replicate p.2 p.1) ++ r) \"\"\n\n/-\n#eval uncompress [(1, 1), (3, 5), (2, 5), (1, 2)] -- returns \"1333332222211\"\n#eval let s := \"1333332222211\" ; uncompress (compress s) = s -- returns true\n-/\n\nend Assignment03\n\nnamespace Chapter3\n\nvariable {a : Type}\n\ndef SymList.reverse : SymList a → SymList a\n | ⟨as, bs, ok⟩ => ⟨bs, as, by exact And.intro ok.2 ok.1⟩\n\n#eval List.toSL [1,2,3] |>.reverse |>.fromSL\n\nexample : ∀ sl : SymList a,\n  List.reverse sl.fromSL = sl.reverse.fromSL := sorry\n\n\n/-\nEm vez de basicamente duplicar o código para as funções no elemento\nda frente e as funções no elemento de trás, poderíamos definir as\nfunções no elemento de trás em termos de reverse e das funções\ncorrespondentes no elemento da frente.\n\nDefina `init` como uma expressão usando `tailSL` e `SymList.reverse`?\n-/\n\ndef SymList.init (q : SymList a) : SymList a  :=\n  q.reverse.tailSL.reverse\n\n-- #eval [1,2,3].toSL |>.init |>.fromSL -- returns [1,2]\n\ndef List.init {α : Type} : List α → List α\n  | []      => []\n  | [_]     => []\n  | x :: xs => x :: init xs\n\n/- agora tente completar a prova seguinte -/\n\nexample : ∀ sl : SymList a,\n  List.init sl.fromSL = sl.init.fromSL := by\n  intro s\n  cases s with\n  | mk as bs ok =>\n    unfold SymList.init SymList.reverse\n    unfold List.init\n    cases as with\n    | nil =>\n      simp\n      cases bs with\n      | nil =>\n        simp [SymList.init, SymList.reverse, SymList.tailSL, SymList.nil]\n      | cons n ns =>\n        simp [SymList.init, SymList.reverse, SymList.tailSL, SymList.nil]\n        sorry\n```\n\nThe proof structure is:\n1. `intro s`: Introduce the `SymList a` variable `s`.\n2. `cases s with | mk as bs ok =>`: Deconstruct `s` into its components `as`, `bs`, and `ok`. The goal becomes `List.init (sl.fromSL) = sl.init.fromSL` where `sl` is `⟨as, bs, ok⟩`.\n3. `unfold SymList.init SymList.reverse`: Unfold the definitions of `SymList.init` and `SymList.reverse` in terms of `SymList.tailSL` and `SymList.reverse`.\n   - `SymList.init q` becomes `q.reverse.tailSL.reverse`.\n   - `q.reverse` becomes `⟨q.2, q.1, ok'⟩` (where `q.1` is `q`'s `as`, `q.2` is `q`'s `bs`, and `ok'` is the reversed predicate).\n4. `unfold List.init`: Unfold the definition of `List.init`.\n   - `List.init l` becomes `match l with | [] => [] | [_] => [] | x :: xs => x :: List.init xs`.\n5. `cases as with | nil => ...`: Case analysis on `as`.\n   - If `as = []`: Then `sl = ⟨[], bs, ok⟩`.\n     - `sl.fromSL` is `List.reverse bs` (assuming `fromSL` takes `as` and `List.reverse bs`).\n     - `List.init (sl.fromSL)` becomes `List.init (List.reverse bs)`.\n     - `sl.init` is `sl.reverse.tailSL.reverse`.\n     - `sl.reverse` is `⟨bs, [], ok'⟩`.\n     - `sl.reverse.tailSL` is `⟨bs, List.tail [], ok''⟩`.\n     - `sl.reverse.tailSL.reverse` is `⟨List.tail [], bs, ok'''⟩`.\n     - `sl.init.fromSL` is `List.reverse (⟨List.tail [], bs, ok'''⟩).fromSL`.\n     - This seems complicated. Let's see what `simp` does.\n6. `simp`: Simplifies the goal using the current definitions.\n   - If `as = []`, `simp` reduces the goal to `List.reverse bs = List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse bs)))` (or something similar, depending on `fromSL`).\n7. `cases bs with | nil => ...`: If `as = []` and `bs = []`, then `sl = ⟨[], [], ok⟩` where `ok` must be `True` (since `List.length [] = 0`).\n   - Goal becomes `List.reverse [] = List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse [])))`, which is `[] = []`.\n   - `simp` should solve this.\n8. `| cons n ns =>`: If `as = []` and `bs = n :: ns`.\n   - Goal becomes `List.reverse (n :: ns) = List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (n :: ns))))`.\n   - `simp` reduces this to `n :: List.reverse ns = n :: List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse ns)))`.\n   - This requires `List.reverse (List.reverse X) = X` for non-empty `X`. This is true.\n   - The `sorry` remains because this path is not fully simplified by `simp`.\n\nLet's complete the proof for the case `as = []` and `bs = n :: ns`:\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter3\nimport Fad.Chapter1\n\nnamespace Assignment03\n\ndef compress (s : String) : List (Nat × Nat) :=\n  help (s.toList.map (·.toNat - '0'.toNat)) []\n where\n  help : List Nat → List (Nat × Nat) → List (Nat × Nat)\n  | []     , acc      => acc.reverse\n  | x :: xs, []       => help xs [(x, 1)]\n  | x :: xs, p :: acc =>\n    if x = p.1\n    then help xs ((p.1, p.2 + 1) :: acc)\n    else help xs ((x, 1) :: p :: acc)\n\n-- #eval compress \"1333332222211\" -- returns [(1, 1), (3, 5), (2, 5), (1, 2)]\n\ndef uncompress : List (Nat × Nat) → String :=\n  let h (xs : List Nat) := xs.foldr (λ a r => s!\"{a}{r}\") \"\"\n  List.foldr (λ p r => h (List.replicate p.2 p.1) ++ r) \"\"\n\n/-\n#eval uncompress [(1, 1), (3, 5), (2, 5), (1, 2)] -- returns \"1333332222211\"\n#eval let s := \"1333332222211\" ; uncompress (compress s) = s -- returns true\n-/\n\nend Assignment03\n\nnamespace Chapter3\n\nvariable {a : Type}\n\ndef SymList.reverse : SymList a → SymList a\n | ⟨as, bs, ok⟩ => ⟨bs, as, by exact And.intro ok.2 ok.1⟩\n\n#eval List.toSL [1,2,3] |>.reverse |>.fromSL\n\nexample : ∀ sl : SymList a,\n  List.reverse sl.fromSL = sl.reverse.fromSL := sorry\n\n\n/-\nEm vez de basicamente duplicar o código para as funções no elemento\nda frente e as funções no elemento de trás, poderíamos definir as\nfunções no elemento de trás em termos de reverse e das funções\ncorrespondentes no elemento da frente.\n\nDefina `init` como uma expressão usando `tailSL` e `SymList.reverse`?\n-/\n\ndef SymList.init (q : SymList a) : SymList a  :=\n  q.reverse.tailSL.reverse\n\n-- #eval [1,2,3].toSL |>.init |>.fromSL -- returns [1,2]\n\ndef List.init {α : Type} : List α → List α\n  | []      => []\n  | [_]     => []\n  | x :: xs => x :: init xs\n\n/- agora tente completar a prova seguinte -/\n\nexample : ∀ sl : SymList a,\n  List.init sl.fromSL = sl.init.fromSL := by\n  intro s\n  cases s with\n  | mk as bs ok =>\n    unfold SymList.init SymList.reverse\n    unfold List.init\n    cases as with\n    | nil =>\n      simp\n      cases bs with\n      | nil =>\n        simp [SymList.init, SymList.reverse, SymList.tailSL, SymList.nil]\n      | cons n ns =>\n        simp [SymList.init, SymList.reverse, SymList.tailSL, SymList.nil]\n        -- Goal is now: n :: List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (List.reverse (n :: List.reverse ns))))))